HIV/AIDS: China reports an increase of 14% in new cases
China has announced an increase of 14°% in the number of people living with HIV or AIDS.
According to health officials, more than 820,000 people are affected in the country.
Approximately 40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
Contrary to the past, the transmission was done in the vast majority of the new cases through sexual intercourse.
To date, HIV spread rapidly in some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people who had been infected with HIV in this way had been reduced to almost zero, Chinese health officials reported at a conference in Yunnan Province.
However, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS has increased by 100,000 in China.
HIV transmission through sex is an acute problem in China's LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT members is expected to be widespread.
Based on the country's conservative values, studies have estimated that 70-90% of men who have sex with men finally marry women.
Many of the disease transmissions are due to insufficient protection of sexual intercourse in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised, among other things, general access to HIV medicines to address the problem.
