Palu and Donggala have been victims of earthquakes and tsunamis several times over the past 100 years, according to the Indonesian Civil Protection Authority.
In 1938, over 200 people were killed by a tsunami that destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
West-Donggala was hit in 1996 by a tsunami in which nine people died.
Indonesia is located on the Seismic Pacific Fire Ring, and is regularly affected by earthquakes.
Here are some of the biggest earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: A strong earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in the north of Sumatras triggered a tsunami on December 26, which struck 14 countries and cost 226,000 people in the coastal areas of the Indish Ocean, of which almost half in Aceh.
2005: A series of severe earthquakes shocked the western coast of Sumatras between the end of March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the Nias Islands in front of the coast of Sumatras.
2006: A strong 6.8 earthquake shocked the southern Javas, Indonesia's most populous island, and triggered a tsunami that hit the south coast and claimed nearly 700 deaths.
2009: A strong 7.6 earthquake met the city of Padang, the capital of the province of West Sumatra.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake with the strength 7.5 shocked one of Mentawai islands in front of Sumatra and triggered a tsunami of up to 10 meters high, destroying dozens of villages and demanding about 300 lives.
2016: A light earthquake shocked the government district Pidie Jaya in Aceh and caused destruction and panic when people were reminded of the destruction of the deadly earthquake and tsunami of 2004.
This time no tsunami was triggered, but more than 100 people died through a crashing building.
2018: Serious earthquakes met the Indonesian island of Lombok, popular among tourists, and, above all, claimed over 500 deaths on the north side of the island.
