Syria is 'ready' for the return of refugees, according to the Foreign Minister
Syria says that it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and requests assistance for the reconstruction of the country devastated by the over seven years of war.
In an address before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said that the situation in the country was improving.
'Today, the situation is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism,' he said.
The government will rebuild the areas destroyed by terrorists in order to restore normality.
All conditions are now provided for the voluntary return of refugees to the country which they had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their everyday lives and living conditions.
The UN estimates that over 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian government welcomed assistance in the reconstruction of the desolate country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept any conditional assistance from countries that had supported the revolt.
