Update to the red time: concentrations in pinellas, manatee and Sarasota decrease
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decline in the concentrations of red tide in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more blooming conditions are recorded in the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, indicating declining concentrations.
A red algae flower extends over about 130 miles of coastline from north Pinellas to south of the district of Lee.
Stains can be found about 10 miles off the coast of the Hillsborough district, but in less places compared to the previous week.
A red time was also observed in Pasco district.
During the last week, average concentrations in or outside the coast of the Pinellas district were reported, low to high concentrations in front of the coast of the Manatee district, background to high concentrations in or outside the coast of the Charlotte district, background to high concentrations in or outside the coast of the Lee district, and low concentrations in the Collier district.
Respiratory problems continue to be reported from the districts Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
In Northwest Florida, no new respiratory problems have been known during the last week.
